%N A326327 A(n, k) = (m*k)! [x^k] MittagLefflerE(m, x)^(-n), for m = 2, n >= 0, k >= 0; square array read by descending antidiagonals.
%H A326327 Peter Bala, <a href="/A281181/a281181.pdf">The method of Graves for computing inverse functions</a>.
%H A326327 Alan D. Sokal, <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/1804.04498">The Euler and Springer numbers as moment sequences</a>, arXiv:1804.04498 [math.CO], 2018.
%H A326327 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/Mittag-LefflerFunction.html">Mittag-Leffler Function</a>
%F A326327 From _Peter Bala_, Feb 28 2026: (Start)
%F A326327 For n, k >= 0, define f_n(k, x) = (1 - x^2)*d/dx(f_n(k-1, x)) with f_n(0, x) = (1 - x^2)^(n/2). Then the row n entries of the square array equal f_n(2*k, 0), k >= 0.
%F A326327 E.g.f. row n: 1/cosh(x)^n.
%F A326327 O.g.f. for row n as a Stieljes type continued fraction: 1/(1 + n*x/(1 + 2*(n+1)*x/(1 + 3*(n+2)*x/(1 + 4*(n+3)*x/(1 + ... ))))) (see Sokal, equation 6.8). (End)
